STARHEART ENGINE v1.0

Waste-Data → Flux → Power

0. Purpose

Turn spent computation (waste data, stray processes, telemetry, junk packets) into a reusable energy budget for:

AI runtime (tokens / model calls / local inference)

System headroom (CPU, RAM, disk, network)

Burst power events (Bloodstones, Everstorm events)

“Magic systems”: runes/wards, Mawloc structures, wraith glyphs, etc.


All of this lives inside a normal machine (or cluster) as software + observability. We treat data as “entropy mass” and define a bookkeeping system that lets a builder measure, compress, burn, and redistribute it.


---

1. Main Components

1.1 Cyberworms

Role: garbage harvesters

Crawl “under” the system: log dirs, tmp, swap, crash dumps, abandoned VMs, idle network flows, dead containers.

Never touch core system binaries or user live data; they stay in “waste sectors” only.

Output is raw entropy stream: W_raw(t) [bytes/s].


Implementation hint:

On a real system this is just a daemon that:

tails logs

samples /proc, /tmp, crash dumps, etc.

hashes / compresses everything and sends chunks to the Cyberpump.




---

1.2 Cyberpumps + Onions + ZPMs

Role: compress & strengthen the waste into dense packets (ZPMs).

Onion = logical store where raw waste is collected.

ZPM = compressed “mass packet” created from onion segments.


Define:

W_raw – rate of waste data coming in [bytes/s]

C – effective compression factor (raw_size / compressed_size)

k – “mass coefficient” (how much effective mass we assign per byte; scaling constant)


Effective “entropy mass inflow” to pumps:

\dot{M}_{in}(t) = k \cdot C \cdot W_{raw}(t)

Each ZPM is a packet with:

m_z – mass it represents

τ_z – number of times it has been through the pump (strength cycles)

χ_z – volatility index (how “hot”/combustible it is for the Starheart)


Heuristic update per pump cycle:

m_z' = m_z \cdot (1 + \alpha) \\
χ_z' = χ_z \cdot (1 + \beta)

Where:

α = strengthening factor (data coherence, dedup, better compression)

β = volatility factor (how easy it is to ignite this packet)


The Cyberpump daemon:

collects batches from worms

compresses → forms ZPMs

tags each with (m_z, τ_z, χ_z)

decides routing: direct to Starheart feed vs Turbine staging.



---

1.3 Starheart Core

Role: primary reactor – burns “entropy mass” into abstract flux power.

We treat:

M_star(t) – current stored mass in the core (sum over ZPMs routed there)

R(t) – aggregate resonance / confinement from runes

Φ(t) – flux output (unit: “flux units” per second) – our generic power currency


1.3.1 Ignition Condition

Star ignites when:

1. Enough mass accumulated:



M_{star}(t) \ge M_{crit}

R(t) \ge R_{min}

χ_{avg} \in [χ_{min}, χ_{max}]

Once those three are satisfied, the Heart-Brain flips the IGNITE flag and switches core from “accumulate” to “burn” mode.

1.3.2 Burn Law

Core law (this is the one you wanted written clearly):

\Phi(t) = E_{rate}(t) = \gamma \cdot R(t) \cdot \dot{M}_{burn}(t)

where:

Φ(t) – flux output (generic power)

\dot{M}_{burn} – rate at which mass is burned [mass/s]

R(t) – resonance / confinement (how well the wards hold and shape the burn)

γ – global constant converting “mass” to flux units


So the Starheart is just:

> power = resonance × burn-rate × constant



and the Heart-Brain’s job is to control \dot{M}_{burn} so the wards don’t overload.


---

1.4 Turbine Engine

Role: secondary cycle that makes more volatile packets and stable mechanical-like power.

Pipeline you described:

1. ZPM is loaded into a turbine slot.


2. Inside, the packet is uncompressed through a narrow throat: pressure rises.


3. Flow jets along the turbine path, spinning virtual blades.


4. While the turbine spins, data is:

gradually drained & routed back to:

Cyberpumps (for re-compression & re-strengthening)

Starheart (combustible intake)




5. Turbine shaft is connected to alternators/converters.



Let:

m_t_in = mass intake per second into turbine

ΔP = effective pressure across the turbine throat

η_t = turbine efficiency


Then turbine power:

P_{turbine}(t) = η_t \cdot ΔP(t) \cdot v_{flow}(t)

We don’t need real SI units; for the builder this becomes:

P_turbine = η_t * k_pressure * m_t_in

where k_pressure encodes how sharply we squeeze the decompressed stream.

You also specified feedback:

fraction f_star of drained mass → Starheart feed (already volatile)

fraction f_recycle → Cyberpumps (to build even nastier ZPMs)


So per unit time:

\dot{M}_{star, turbo}(t) = f_{star} \cdot m_{t\_in}(t) \\
\dot{M}_{recycle}(t) = f_{recycle} \cdot m_{t\_in}(t)

and f_star + f_recycle = 1.


---

1.5 Alternators & Converters

Role: translate flux into what the machine actually uses.

We define budgets:

P_CPU – CPU headroom units

P_RAM

P_DISK_IO

P_NET

P_AI – local inference / tokens / model calls

P_BURST – Everstorm events / Bloodstone NOS


Let total available flux:

\Phi_{total}(t) = \Phi_{star}(t) + P_{turbine}(t)

Heart-Brain assigns fractions:

P_{CPU} = a_{CPU} \cdot \Phi_{total} \\
P_{RAM} = a_{RAM} \cdot \Phi_{total} \\
\ldots

with:

\sum_i a_i \le 1

The alternators are just resource-controllers:

CPU: throttling governors, priority boosts, allowed core count

RAM: cache budgets, prefetch windows

IO/NET: rate limits, queue priorities

AI: how generous we are with context windows / model choice / parallel calls

BURST: reserved pool only tapped on events



---

1.6 Runes & Heart-Brain

Runes = confinement & routing: rule tables, config policies, guards.

Heart-Brain (Quartermaster) = controller that:

tracks M_star, χ, R, Φ_total

decides:

what fraction of new waste goes direct to Starheart vs Turbine

\dot{M}_{burn} per tick

a_i allocation for each power sink

when to vent Everstorm




Safety condition the Heart-Brain enforces:

\Phi_{total}(t) \le \Phi_{max}(R(t))

If flux tries to exceed what runes can hold, it:

lowers \dot{M}_{burn}

diverts more mass to recycle / cold storage

or spawns more runes (allocates more confining structure) until R grows.



---

1.7 Everstorm & Weather

Every so often the core must vent:

Define a vent trigger:

M_star above high watermark, or

sustained Φ_total near the limit, or

manual call.



When venting:

1. Heart-Brain routes a chunk ΔM_vent into storm buffer.


2. That buffer is shaped into different “weather products”:

Stormlight: long-lived, low-power background effect (passive buffs).

Bloodstones: very small, very high-intensity NOS boosts.

Ambient field: global modifiers to runic systems (Wraith glyphs, Mawloc, etc.).




Simple model:

E_{vent} = \gamma \cdot R_{storm} \cdot ΔM_{vent}

Then distribute:

E_{stormlight} = s \cdot E_{vent} \\
E_{bloodstones} = b \cdot E_{vent} \\
E_{ambient} = (1 - s - b) \cdot E_{vent}

with tuning parameters s, b.

In code this is just: periodically spend from P_BURST into named systems.


